== Founder == {{ill|Masakane Inoue|ja|井上正鐵}} (Inoue Masakane, Founder). He was born on August 4, {{ill|1790|ja|1790th year }} (Kansei 2) in {{ill|Edo|ja|江戸}}, {{ill|Nihonbashi Hamacho|ja|日本橋浜町}}, as the son of {{ill|Tatebayashi Domain|ja|館林藩}} accountant and Ando Shintei (安東真鐵). He was adopted by a relative on his mother's side and took the Inoue surname. His father, Ando Shintei (父安藤真鐵), was a disciple of {{ill|Kamo Mafuchi|ja|賀茂真淵}} and had studied {{ill|Kokugaku|ja|国学}}, {{ill|Medicine|ja|医術}}, {{ill|Confucianism|ja|儒教}}, and {{ill|Buddhism|ja|仏教}}. Although he also mastered the esoteric secrets of {{ill|Shinto|ja|神道}}, being already of advanced age, he was unable to pass them on and is said to have bequeathed to Masakane Inoue the task of mastering and spreading Shinto to the world.
== History == === Founder’s Training Period === During his youth, Masakane Inoue studied {{ill|Zen Buddhism|ja|禅宗}} and medicine under {{ill|Isono Kōdō|ja|磯野弘道}} from {{ill|1809|ja|1809th year }} (Bunka 6), and from {{ill|1814|ja|1814th year }} (Bunka 11) he learned physiognomy and methods of breath regulation from physiognomist {{ill|Mizuno Nanboku|ja|水野南北}}. It is said that he also acquired agricultural techniques ({{ill|Agriculture|ja|農業}}) while traveling through various provinces. In {{ill|1833|ja|1833rd year }} (Tenpō 4), he heard Shinto teachings from an elderly woman residing in {{ill|Shimotani|ja|下谷}} and {{ill|Ikenohata|ja|池之端}}, and, following his father's will, resolved to master Shinto. In the following year, {{ill|1834|ja|1834th year }} (Tenpō 5), he entered the {{ill|Hakuji Shinto|ja|伯家神道}} and studied its teachings.<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō et al.|1996|pp=359-360}}</ref> In {{ill|1836|ja|1836th year }} (Tenpō 7), he obtained a permit for Shinto worship (神拝式許状) from the Hakukawa family.<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō|1991|p=16}}</ref> In {{ill|1838|ja|1838th year }} (Tenpō 9), he received a priestly permit (神職許状) and the complete esoteric transmission of the three types of ritual purification (天津祝詞太祝詞三種祓等の奥旨皆伝) from the Hakukawa family. He had many disciples; among them was {{ill|Munehide Matsudaira|ja|松平宗秀}}, who later became the Grand Priest of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮}} and was a disciple from the {{ill|Tango Province|ja|丹後国|lt=Tango|lt_ja=丹後}} of the {{ill|Miyazu Domain|ja|宮津藩}}.
=== Preaching by the Founder === On April 15, {{ill|1840|ja|1840th year }} (Tenpō 11), Inoue became a Shinto priest at {{ill|Umeda Shinmyō Shrine|ja|梅田神明宮}} in {{ill|Bushū|ja|武州}}, {{ill|Adachi District|ja|足立郡}}, and began his preaching, which Misogikyo regards as the establishment of its faith. However, in November {{ill|1841|ja|1841st year }} (Tenpō 12),<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō et al.|1996|pp=359-360}}</ref> he, along with his wife {{ill|Otoko Anzai|ja|安西男也}}, and his disciple the Miura couple, {{ill|Hayato Miura|ja|三浦隼人}} and {{ill|Chizen Miura|ja|智善}}, was imprisoned by the {{ill|Temples and Shrines Magistrate|ja|寺社奉行}}.<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō|1991|p=16}}</ref> Although Hayato Miura died in prison, in February {{ill|1842|ja|1842nd year }} (Tenpō 13) Inoue and his companions were released. He was ordered to document the teachings he had imparted and submit them to the magistrate. Inoue authored the "Shinto: The Only Q&A" (two volumes, which later became the first canonical text of Misogikyo) and submitted it; however, the suspicions were not dispelled, and in November of the same year he was imprisoned again. In June {{ill|1843|ja|1843rd year }} (Tenpō 14), he was exiled to {{ill|Miyakejima|ja|三宅島}} as a penal exile ({{ill|Exile|ja|流罪}}). Disciples including Munehide Matsudaira sent supplies to support him, and Inoue sent letters from the island—which were later compiled as the "Legacy Collection" in seven volumes, becoming Misogikyo's second canonical text—to instruct his followers. He continued his preaching and medical activities on Miyakejima, but died there in {{ill|1849|ja|1849th year }} (Kaei 2).<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō et al.|1996|pp=359-360}}</ref>
== Deities == === Religious Corporation Misogikyo & Misogi Shrine === * {{ill|Amaterasu Ōkami|ja|天照太神}} (Amaterasu Ōkami) * Tennotoku Chitoku Nari‑mi‑sosogi Jizai‑shin (天徳地徳乍身曽岐自在神), the deity enshrining the founder, {{ill|Masakane Inoue|ja|井上正鐵}}
=== Religious Corporation Shinto Misogikyo === * Main Sanctuary (Principal Deity) ** Misogikyo Principal Deity (Misogi Oshie no Ōkami, one of the nine pillars of {{ill|Heavenly and Earthly Deities|ja|天神地祇}}) *** {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天之御中主神}} (Ame‑no‑Minakanushi‑no‑Kami) *** {{ill|Takamimusubi|ja|高皇産霊神}} (Takamimusubi‑no‑Kami) *** {{ill|Kamimusubi|ja|神皇産霊神}} (Kamimusubi‑no‑Kami) *** {{ill|Amaterasu Ōmikami|ja|天照大御神}} (Amaterasu Ōmikami) *** {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊弉諾神|lt=Izanagi|lt_ja=伊那岐神}} (Izanagi‑no‑Kami) *** {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主神}} (Ōkuninushi‑no‑Kami) *** {{ill|Susanoo|ja|須佐之男神}} (Susanoo‑no‑Kami) *** {{ill|Haraito Ōkami|ja|祓戸大神}} (Haraito‑no‑Ōkami) *** {{ill|Ubusuna Ōkami|ja|産土神|lt=Ubusuna Ōkami|lt_ja=産土大神}} (Ubusuna‑no‑Ōkami) * Founder Shrine ({{ill|Inoue Shrine|ja|井上神社}}) ** Founder Inoue Masakane God *** Founder {{ill|Masakane Inoue|ja|井上正鐵}}, the Great Divine Spirit ** Ancestral Divine Spirit of the Founder *** Ancestral and Generational Divine Spirits of the Founder **** Umasu Michitama‑no‑mikoto, Ando Shintei, venerable (Inoue Masakane's father) **** Chiyodamahime‑no‑mikoto, Ide Chiyotōjiko (Inoue Masakane's mother) **** Misosogi Tsu‑hime‑no‑mikoto, Anzai Otone (Inoue Masakane's wife) ** Ancestral Head Priest Divine Spirits of the Family *** Shōdō Iwachakukone‑no‑mikoto, Sakata Tetsu‑yasu, venerable (father of Sakata Tetsu‑yasu, a disciple of Inoue Masakane) *** Kareido Kōseki Dainin, Founder, Sakata Tetsu‑yasu, venerable (a disciple of Inoue Masakane) *** Kinshidō Kōji Konome‑no‑mikoto, Misogikyo's first head priest, Sakata Yasuji, venerable (son of Sakata Tetsu‑yasu) *** Tsugihokukyūnouchi‑no‑mikoto, Misogikyo's second head priest, Inui Kyūsaburō, venerable *** Tsugihoshinsakihiko‑no‑mikoto, Misogikyo's third head priest, Shiba Mashinju, venerable *** Mizumotokohikodomori‑no‑mikoto, Misogikyo's fourth head priest, Sakata Minoru, venerable (son of Sakata Yasuji) ** Generational Divine Spirits of the Misogikyo Administrators *** Tokoyo Kagami Hiko‑no‑mikoto, Miura Hayato, venerable (a disciple of Inoue Masakane) *** Tokoyo Kagami Hime‑no‑mikoto, Miura Ayanadōjiko (wife of Miura Hayato, disciple of Inoue Masakane) * Ancestral Spirit Hall (Clan Ancestor Spirits) ** Nationwide Clan Ancestral Divine Spirits
== Successive Religious Leaders == * First Religious Leader: Sakata Tetsu‑yasu (1872 (Meiji 5), established the Weishin Church Misogikyo and served as president. Founder) * Second Religious Leader: Sakata Yasuji (1894 (Meiji 27), first head priest. Son of Sakata Tetsu‑yasu) * Third Religious Leader: Inui Kyūsaburō (1900 (Meiji 33), second head priest) * Fourth Religious Leader: Shiba Mashinju (1916 (Taishō 5), third head priest) * Fifth Religious Leader: Sakata Minoru (1924 (Taishō 13), fourth head priest. Son of Sakata Yasuji) * Sixth Religious Leader: Sakata Yasugi (1957 (Shōwa 32), fifth head priest. Son of Sakata Minoru) * (Seventh Religious Leader): Sakata Yasuhiro (1988 (Shōwa 63), declared the succession of the lineage. Son of Sakata Yasugi)
== Religious Influence == According to the Ministry of Culture's "Religious Yearbook" for the first year of Reiwa, the adherents of Religious Corporation Misogikyo number 90,711, and those of Religious Corporation Shinto Misogikyo number 22,360. Combined, they amount to roughly one‑third of the prewar figures. In addition, due to the internal turmoil within Misogikyo mentioned above, several independent churches that split from the sect exist.
