{{Short description|Shinto sect}} {{nihongo|'''Misogikyo'''|禊教}} is a {{ill|Sect Shinto|ja|教派神道|qq=draft}} organization and one of the thirteen Shinto sects.<ref>{{Cite book |last=井上 |first=順孝 |title= |date=April 1991 |publisher=弘文堂 |isbn=978-4335160219 |page=11 |script-title=ja:教派神道の形成 |author-link=井上順孝}}</ref>
It is considered a "purification sect" alongside {{ill|Shinshu-kyo|ja|Shinshu-kyo|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kyōha Shintō {{!}} Japanese religion |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Kyoha-Shinto |access-date=2023-03-06 |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |language=en}}</ref>
Its name literally means {{ill|Misogi|ja|禊|qq=draft}} religion
The group is quite obscure today<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Sawada |first=Janine Anderson |date=1998 |title=Mind and Morality in Nineteenth-Century Japanese Religions: Misogi-Kyō and Maruyama-Kyō |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1399927 |journal=Philosophy East and West |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=108–141 |doi=10.2307/1399927 |issn=0031-8221}}</ref> It is very ritual‑focused with little theoretical theology. In this way it contrasts with {{ill|Yoshida Shinto|ja|吉田神道|qq=draft}}.<ref name=":0" /> It emphasizes the right state of mind and self‑control<ref name=":0" /> It has influence from {{ill|Confucian Shinto|ja|儒教神道|qq=draft}} but is its own tradition.<ref name=":0" />
== Sources == * https://www.jstor.org/stable/1399927
== Overview == {{infobox organization | name = '''Misogikyo''' (禊教) | image = File:P1000772 misogi 2.JPG | image_size = 280 | image_caption = {{ill|Misogi Shrine|ja|身曾岐神社|qq=draft}} | image2 = | image_size2 = | image_caption2 = | map = {{maplink2|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=point|zoom=12|frame-align=center|frame-width=280|coord={{coord|35|51|46.1|N|138|20|12.5|E}}}} | abbreviation = | established = 1840 (Tenpō 11) | dissolved = | type = {{ill|Religious Corporation|ja|宗教法人|qq=draft}} | status = | purpose = | headquarters = {{ill|Yamanashi Prefecture|ja|山梨県|qq=draft}}{{ill|Hokuto City|ja|北杜市|qq=draft}}小淵沢町上笹尾3401 | coords = {{Wiki coordinates 2-stage DMS|35|51|46.1|N|138|20|12.5|E|display=inline,title}} | location = | language = | founder = {{ill|Masakane Inoue|ja|井上正鐵|qq=draft}} | notable_people = | affiliated_organizations = | institutions = | leader_title = Head Priest | leader_name = {{ill|Yasugi Sakata|ja|坂田安儀|qq=draft}} | website = }}
'''Misogikyo''' (禊教) is a branch of {{ill|Sect Shinto|ja|教派神道|qq=draft}} that inherits the teachings of {{ill|Masakane Inoue|ja|井上正鐵|qq=draft}}, who studied Zen, physiognomy, medicine, and {{ill|Hakuji Shinto|ja|伯家神道|qq=draft}}. It is under the jurisdiction of the {{ill|Minister of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology|ja|文部科学大臣|qq=draft}} and is a {{ill|Comprehensive Religious Corporation|ja|包括宗教法人|qq=draft}}.
