=== Preaching by the Founder === On April 15, {{ill|1840|ja|1840th year|qq=draft}} (Tenpō 11), Inoue became a Shinto priest at {{ill|Umeda Shinmyō Shrine|ja|梅田神明宮|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Bushū|ja|武州|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Adachi District|ja|足立郡|qq=draft}}, and began his preaching, which Misogikyo regards as the establishment of its faith. However, in November {{ill|1841|ja|1841st year|qq=draft}} (Tenpō 12),<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō et al.|1996|pp=359-360}}</ref> he, along with his wife {{ill|Otoko Anzai|ja|安西男也|qq=draft}}, and his disciple the Miura couple, {{ill|Hayato Miura|ja|三浦隼人|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Chizen Miura|ja|智善|qq=draft}}, was imprisoned by the {{ill|Temples and Shrines Magistrate|ja|寺社奉行|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō|1991|p=16}}</ref> Although Hayato Miura died in prison, in February {{ill|1842|ja|1842nd year|qq=draft}} (Tenpō 13) Inoue and his companions were released. He was ordered to document the teachings he had imparted and submit them to the magistrate. Inoue authored the "Shinto: The Only Q&A" (two volumes, which later became the first canonical text of Misogikyo) and submitted it; however, the suspicions were not dispelled, and in November of the same year he was imprisoned again. In June {{ill|1843|ja|1843rd year|qq=draft}} (Tenpō 14), he was exiled to {{ill|Miyakejima|ja|三宅島|qq=draft}} as a penal exile ({{ill|Exile|ja|流罪|qq=draft}}). Disciples including Munehide Matsudaira sent supplies to support him, and Inoue sent letters from the island—which were later compiled as the "Legacy Collection" in seven volumes, becoming Misogikyo's second canonical text—to instruct his followers. He continued his preaching and medical activities on Miyakejima, but died there in {{ill|1849|ja|1849th year|qq=draft}} (Kaei 2).<ref>{{sfn|Inoue Junkō et al.|1996|pp=359-360}}</ref>
