{{Short description|Shinto sect}} {{nihongo|'''Misogikyo'''|禊教}} is a [[:en:Sect Shinto|Sect Shinto]] organization and one of the thirteen Shinto sects.<ref>{{Cite book |last=井上 |first=順孝 |title= |date=April 1991 |publisher=弘文堂 |isbn=978-4335160219 |page=11 |script-title=ja:教派神道の形成 |author-link=井上順孝}}</ref>
It is considered a "purification sect" alongside {{ill|Shinshu-kyo|ja|Shinshu-kyo|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinshu-kyo|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Kyōha Shintō {{!}} Japanese religion |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Kyoha-Shinto |access-date=2023-03-06 |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |language=en}}</ref>
Its name literally means [[:en:Misogi|Misogi]] religion
The group is quite obscure today<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal |last=Sawada |first=Janine Anderson |date=1998 |title=Mind and Morality in Nineteenth-Century Japanese Religions: Misogi-Kyō and Maruyama-Kyō |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1399927 |journal=Philosophy East and West |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=108–141 |doi=10.2307/1399927 |issn=0031-8221}}</ref> It is very ritual‑focused with little theoretical theology. In this way it contrasts with [[:en:Yoshida Shintō|Yoshida Shinto]].<ref name=":0" /> It emphasizes the right state of mind and self‑control<ref name=":0" /> It has influence from {{ill|Confucian Shinto|ja|儒教神道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Confucian Shinto|qq=}} but is its own tradition.<ref name=":0" />
